techmeme.title: Source: at the end of March, Bolt's annualized run rate was $28M in revenue and $7M in gross profit, making a funding round at a $14B valuation hard to believe (Eric Newcomer/Newcomer)
A US district judge in Texas strikes down the FTC's ban on worker noncompete agreements, due to start September 4, after her temporary block of the rule in July (Daniel Wiessner/Reuters)
In a Reddit AMA, CEO Patrick Spence said Sonos won't rerelease its old app, after testing showed that doing so "would make the problems worse, not better" (Jay Peters/The Verge)
Filing: chipmaker Microchip Technology says its servers were breached by an unauthorized party, causing its operations to run at "less than normal levels" (Nick Turner/Bloomberg)
A US appeals court revives a class action suit by Google Chrome users who say Google collected personal info even if Chrome was not synced with a Google account (Jonathan Stempel/Reuters)
